01:03:47.650 --> 01:03:50.770
I am a conservative on this issue.

01:03:50.770 --> 01:03:55.660
I think the Qur'an came
through the prophet Muhammad.

01:03:55.660 --> 01:04:00.540
And I think that the traditional
dating of it, 610-632 --

01:04:00.540 --> 01:04:04.030
you could tinker with it,
but it's just about right.

01:04:04.030 --> 01:04:06.460
And I find contemporary
things being referred to.

01:04:06.460 --> 01:04:10.780 position:56%
Like we know when the Byzantines
were defeated by the Iranians and so

01:04:10.780 --> 01:04:17.700
that verse which talks about
it must be from 614, 615.

01:04:17.700 --> 01:04:19.640
It must be from that period.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:26.070
So there is now some evidence
for the integrity of the Qur'an

01:04:26.070 --> 01:04:30.130
and for the traditional dating
coming out of manuscript work.

01:04:30.130 --> 01:04:34.820
But in the 1980's I went to Yemen

01:04:34.820 --> 01:04:38.580 position:56%
and they have a manuscript
repository in Yemen which, you know,

01:04:38.580 --> 01:04:41.790
for any historian it's
just wonderful.

01:04:41.790 --> 01:04:44.620
But they found these old, old, old,

01:04:44.620 --> 01:04:47.280
Qur'ans in the Great
Mosque in Yemen.

01:04:47.280 --> 01:04:52.140
And they brought in the Germans
to assemble them and study them.

01:04:52.140 --> 01:04:57.400
And I talk to Ursula Dreibholtz
who is in charge of this project.

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:00.670 position:56%
And she said, "We're quite convinced
that some of these, you know,

01:05:00.670 --> 01:05:06.820
the papyrus, the script,
they look to us 7th century."

01:05:06.820 --> 01:05:12.230
And then one of them turned
out to be a palimpsest.

01:05:12.230 --> 01:05:17.980 position:56%
Palimpsest is in the old days, you
know, paper or papyrus and so forth.

01:05:17.980 --> 01:05:19.660
Parchment was expensive.

01:05:19.660 --> 01:05:22.190
People would write over things.

01:05:22.190 --> 01:05:30.220
So they found one of these
Qur'ans which was in the 650's,

01:05:30.220 --> 01:05:33.200
the Caliph Uthman published
a standard Qur'an

01:05:33.200 --> 01:05:36.170
which is all the printed
Qur'ans you have are from that.

01:05:36.170 --> 01:05:41.480
That underneath the standard
Qur'an was an earlier one.

01:05:41.480 --> 01:05:43.270
And they radio carbon dated it.

01:05:43.270 --> 01:05:47.090
And you know, you don't get exact
figures from radio carbon dating,

01:05:47.090 --> 01:05:49.830
but you get percentage likelihoods.

01:05:49.830 --> 01:05:54.970
Percentage likelihood
of this one, 645.

01:05:54.970 --> 01:05:58.250 position:56%
And it's not the standard recension.

01:05:58.250 --> 01:06:01.440
The order of the chapters
is slightly different.

01:06:01.440 --> 01:06:03.730
Not a lot of -- you know,
there are variations,

01:06:03.730 --> 01:06:06.100
but not a lot of significant ones.

01:06:06.100 --> 01:06:09.930
But if we now have a
Qur'an 645, the likelihood

01:06:09.930 --> 01:06:17.710
of the text we have being integral
is much higher than it used to be.

01:06:17.710 --> 01:06:21.840
There's also been a find
in Paris at Birmingham

01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:24.000
of 16 pages of the Qur'an.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:31.700
Two of them have been carbon
dated and they came back 570-640.

01:06:31.700 --> 01:06:36.350 position:56%
